## Quote Formatting

### Semantic Quote Structure
Use semantic HTML5 `<figure>`, `<blockquote>`, and `<figcaption>` elements:

```html
<figure class="quote">
<blockquote>
Quote text goes here without quotation marks or italics.
</blockquote>
<figcaption>
&mdash; Attribution Name or Source
</figcaption>
</figure>
```

**Rules:**
- Always use `<figure class="quote">` wrapper
- Use `<blockquote>` for the quote text (no quotation marks, no italics)
- Use `<figcaption>` with `&mdash;` for attribution
- Remove markdown quote syntax (`>`) and formatting (`*`)
- Place quotes where they enhance the content flow
- Use "Tao of the Video Editor" as attribution for course quotes

**Example:**
```html
<figure class="quote">
<blockquote>
The medium shapes the message. The editor shapes both.
</blockquote>
<figcaption>
&mdash; Tao of the Video Editor
</figcaption>
</figure>
```

**Before (Markdown):**
```markdown
> *"The medium shapes the message. The editor shapes both."*
```

**After (Semantic HTML):**
```html
<figure class="quote">
<blockquote>
The medium shapes the message. The editor shapes both.
</blockquote>
<figcaption>
&mdash; Tao of the Video Editor
</figcaption>
</figure>
```

### Quote Placement Guidelines
- Place quotes at natural breaks in content
- Use quotes to emphasize key concepts
- Ensure quotes support the surrounding text
- Don't overuse quotes—quality over quantity

---

*These rules ensure consistent, accessible, and maintainable media integration across all lesson content.*
